Here's a minor feature request for exporting to GCC and GCC-based environments (such as KDS and Atmel Studio): add the compiler flag`-funsigned-char` in exported projects by default.
)
The mbed handbook lists the `char` type as being unsigned ([here](https://developer.mbed.org/handbook/C-Data-Types)), but the C standard does not specify, and in GCC `char`s are signed by default (see http://stackoverflow.com/a/2054959/1858923). This leads to errors when exporting projects that assume that `char`s are unsigned, such as [Neil Thiessen's SDFileSystem](https://developer.mbed.org/users/neilt6/code/SDFileSystem/). If we automatically set `-funsigned-char` in exported projects, we reduce the inconsistencies between the mbed online compiler and other target compilers for exported projects.

STM32F0x has OSC_IN and OSC_OUT pins coupled with PF0 and PF_1.
If external oscillator is used then HSE must not be enabled. Otherwise PF0 will be occupied by RCC and can't be used as GPIO.

Current code use default values for init structure:

``` CPP
uint8_t SetSysClock_PLL_HSI(void)
{
  RCC_ClkInitTypeDef RCC_ClkInitStruct;
  RCC_OscInitTypeDef RCC_OscInitStruct;

  // Select PLLCLK = 48 MHz ((HSI 8 MHz / 2) * 12)
  RCC_OscInitStruct.OscillatorType          = RCC_OSCILLATORTYPE_HSI;
  RCC_OscInitStruct.HSIState                = RCC_HSI_ON;
  RCC_OscInitStruct.PLL.PLLState            = RCC_PLL_ON;
  RCC_OscInitStruct.PLL.PLLSource           = RCC_PLLSOURCE_HSI; // HSI div 2
  RCC_OscInitStruct.PLL.PREDIV              = RCC_PREDIV_DIV2;
  RCC_OscInitStruct.PLL.PLLMUL              = RCC_PLL_MUL12;
  if (HAL_RCC_OscConfig(&RCC_OscInitStruct) != HAL_OK) {
      return 0; // FAIL
  }
```

However `RCC_OscInitTypeDef` has few important fields that must be set to prevent accidental HSE activation. Critical one is `RCC_OscInitStruct.HSICalibrationValue`.

Interesting that F031K6 and F042K6 set it but all other platform ignore.

I have been testing stop mode on the STM32F4 processors for an application. I've noticed a couple issues:

1) When using the online compiler, I need to include the mbed-rtos library in my project in order for the device to ever wake up from stop mode. If I remove the rtos library from my project and rebuild, my device never wakes up. The application is using mbed library revision 112 and mbed-rtos revision 101. All beta modes are turned off. I've reproduced this issue with both F411 Nucleo and F401 Nucleo boards. My application can be found [here](https://developer.mbed.org/users/mfiore/code/stm32f4-stop-mode/).

2) When building this same application offline using the mbed sdk (mbed_lib_rev112 tag) and the arm-none-eabi toolchain (version 4.9.3.2015q3-1trusty1 on 64 bit Ubuntu 14.04), I need to go even further to get the application to function properly. Simply invoking the make script with the --rtos option isn't enough; I have to actually include the rtos header and put a thread into my application for the device to properly wake up from stop mode. The following modified version of the original application works when the --rtos option is used with the make script. This was again verified on both the F411 Nucleo and F401 Nucleo boards.

``` c++
#include "mbed.h"
#include "rtos.h"
#include <time.h>
#include <rtc_api.h>

DigitalOut led(LED1);

void thread_func(const void*) {
    while (true) {
        led = !led;
        osDelay(200);
    }
}

int is_rtc_enabled(void) {
    return (RTC ->ISR & RTC_ISR_INITS ) && (RTC ->ISR & RTC_ISR_RSF );
}

int main() {
    // attach our custom RTC enabled function so time can survive across sleeps & resets
    attach_rtc(&rtc_read, &rtc_write, &rtc_init, &is_rtc_enabled);
    if (!is_rtc_enabled()) 
        set_time(0);
    RTC_HandleTypeDef RtcHandle;
    RtcHandle.Instance = RTC;

    Thread t(thread_func);

    int interval = 4;

    while(true) {

        __PWR_CLK_ENABLE();
        HAL_PWR_EnableBkUpAccess();

        HAL_PWREx_EnableMainRegulatorLowVoltage();
        HAL_PWREx_EnableFlashPowerDown();
        HAL_PWREx_EnableLowRegulatorLowVoltage();

        // make sure RTC and LSE stay on while we're asleep
        RCC ->BDCR |= RCC_BDCR_LSEON;
        RCC ->BDCR |= RCC_BDCR_RTCEN;

        printf("configuring wakeup timer for %lu seconds from now\r\n", interval);

        HAL_RTCEx_SetWakeUpTimer_IT(&RtcHandle, interval, RTC_WAKEUPCLOCK_CK_SPRE_16BITS );

        printf("entering sleep mode %08x\r\n", RTC->ISR);
        fflush(stdout);

        // clear any pending interrupts
        EXTI ->PR = (1 << 22);

        HAL_PWR_EnterSTOPMode(PWR_LOWPOWERREGULATOR_ON, PWR_STOPENTRY_WFI );

        HAL_PWREx_DisableMainRegulatorLowVoltage();
        HAL_PWREx_DisableFlashPowerDown();
        HAL_PWREx_DisableLowRegulatorLowVoltage();

        __HAL_RTC_WAKEUPTIMER_CLEAR_FLAG(&RtcHandle, RTC_FLAG_WUTF);

        // reconfigure PLL
        SetSysClock();
        wait(1.0);
        printf("wake\r\n");    
    }

    return 0;    
}
```

I noticed that the online compiler seems to be building the rtos library from source (and linking against it), while the offline mbed sdk links against the rtos archive generated when the build script is run. Is this difference be part of the issue?

I noticed that the rtos library has additional startup code for the each toolchain. Does this replace the startup code in the standard mbed library or are they both used? Is there some critical piece of startup code that is only getting executed when the rtos library is involved?

